Dear Dr. Patel,

Thank you for our telephone conversation on October 22 regarding the Meridian Corporation v. Pinnacle Industries patent infringement case. I am writing to formally engage you as an expert witness on behalf of Meridian Corporation.

As we discussed, Meridian has filed a patent infringement action against Pinnacle Industries in the Northern District of California, alleging that Pinnacle's AutoForge Multi-Stage Compression Platform infringes U.S. Patent No. 9,876,543, entitled "Multi-Stage Thermal Compression Molding System and Method for Advanced Composite Materials." The patent covers a novel approach to thermal compression molding that uses multi-stage compression with thermal compression boundary layer management.

We are retaining you to serve as our technical expert on manufacturing process infringement. Specifically, we will ask you to:

1. Review the '543 Patent, its prosecution history, and the accused AutoForge System documentation;
2. Perform a detailed element-by-element comparison of the AutoForge System against Claims 1-14 of the '543 Patent;
3. Prepare a written expert report setting forth your opinions on infringement;
4. Provide deposition testimony, if required by opposing counsel;
5. Provide testimony at trial, if the case does not settle.

We have confirmed your availability and standard engagement terms: $650 per hour for all work performed, with a $5,000 retainer to be paid upon execution of the engagement letter. Travel time will be billed at half rate, and reasonable travel expenses will be reimbursed.

I am attaching the following materials for your initial review:
- U.S. Patent No. 9,876,543 (complete patent document)
- The Technology License Agreement between Meridian and Pinnacle
- Publicly available marketing materials for the AutoForge System
- The Complaint filed in this action

Additional discovery materials will be provided as they become available. We anticipate receiving Pinnacle's engineering documentation for the AutoForge System in the coming months through the discovery process.

We would like to schedule an initial meeting — either in person at your Stanford office or via videoconference — during the week of November 3 to discuss the case in detail and begin your analysis. Please let me know your availability, and we will coordinate.

The expert report deadline is currently set for May 30, 2026, but we would like to have a preliminary analysis completed by January 2026 to support our claim construction briefing and potential summary judgment motion.

Please review and countersign the attached engagement letter and return it to my attention at your earliest convenience. We are excited to have your expertise on this important matter.

